style=3D"DISPLAY: none">&nbsp;</SPAN></SPAN></SPAN>=96 Synthesis, =
Crystallization,=20
and Recrystallization of the Iron Salt</H2>
<P class=3DMsoNormal>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
12pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =

<B>Synthesis:</B></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Weigh 24.0 g of=20
K<SUB>2</SUB>C<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>4</SUB></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Symbol">=B7</SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">H<SUB>2</SUB>O (MW 184.2 =
<SUP>g</SUP>/<SUB>mol</SUB>)=20
into a clean dry 100 mL beaker.&nbsp; Record all decimal =
places.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN: 6pt 0in 0pt 0.75in"><B><I>NOTE:</I></B><I>&nbsp; Always =
record=20
measurements to the correct precision and use glassware that will =
provide the=20
needed precision while still providing the quickest measurement.&nbsp; =
The=20
precision or amount of digits past the decimal can tell you what type of =

glassware or instrumentation to use. The table on precision of glassware =
in the=20
introduction provides the precision of various types of glassware. In =
deciding=20
what glassware to use, use the required precision, capacity of =
glassware, and=20
time for measurement to make your decision.</I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
0.25in"><I>For=20
example, 10 mL could be measured with a 250 mL graduated cylinder =
because it has=20
a precision of </I><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol">=B1</SPAN>1 mL =
that=20
is&nbsp; less than 10 mL volume to be measured but a 10 mL graduated =
cylinder=20
would be much better with a precision of </I><I><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol">=B1</SPAN>0.05 mL. They would both take =
about the same=20
amount of time to use but the 10 mL would be much more precise.&nbsp; =
Any=20
glassware that is more precise (it has a precision less than =
</I><I><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol">=B1</SPAN>1 mL) could also be used.&nbsp; =
The only=20
glassware that can=92t be used to measure a 10 mL volume is a =
beaker.&nbsp; Its=20
precision is </I><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol">=B1</SPAN>10 mL, =
so=20
measuring a 10 mL volume would not be useful and so the actual volume =
could=20
range from ~5 to 15 mL.&nbsp; Side Note: a measurement of <U>about</U> =
10 mL is=20
a really sloppy measurement.&nbsp; A small beaker could be used for=20
this.</I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
0.25in"><I>Usually=20
you want to obtain the best required precision in the least amount of=20
time.&nbsp; For example, when measuring 10.0 mL of a liquid, a 10.00 mL=20
volumetric pipet takes a lot longer to deliver the same liquid when =
compared to=20
10.0 mL from a 10 mL graduated cylinder.&nbsp; The pipet is also harder =
to=20
clean, so the graduated cylinder would be the best choice to =
use.</I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
0.25in"><I>You will=20
also have the option of using a 5 or 10 mL pipettor for 1-10 mL=20
transfers.</I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN: 6pt 0in 0pt 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Add about 60 mL of RO water, heat gently (hot =
plate=20
setting of low or 2, each hot plate is different), and stir to =
dissolve.&nbsp;=20
To stir, use a clean Teflon stir bar, and set the hot plate at a =
moderate=20
speed.&nbsp; (Figure A-1.)</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN: 3pt 0in; TEXT-ALIGN: center"=20
align=3Dcenter><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><IMG height=3D56=20
src=3D"http://jan.ucc.nau.edu/~jkn/152A-SynthesisIronSalt_files/image001.=
jpg"=20
width=3D143></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">While this is dissolving, clean a wash bottle, =
25 mL=20
graduated cylinder, 100 mL beaker, watch glass, and a wide mouth amber =
bottle.=20
Your TA will provide the amber bottle.&nbsp; Fill the wash bottle with =
RO=20
water.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></SPAN><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">When the=20
K<SUB>2</SUB>C<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>4</SUB></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Symbol">=B7</SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">H<SUB>2</SUB>O is dissolved add 16.0 mL of =
0.400 g/mL=20
FeCl<SUB>3</SUB> and stir for about one minute and remove the stir bar. =
Use the=20
magnetic stir bar retriever on the outside of the beaker to remove the =
stir bar=20
(see TA for demo).</SPAN></P>
<P=20
class=3DMsoNormal>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&=
nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
<B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Crystallization:</SPAN></B></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Remove the solution from heat and let cool for =
about 20=20
minutes.&nbsp; Exchange names and workstation/bin numbers (record in =
your=20
notebook) while waiting.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Cool the solution for another 40-60 min. in a =
slurry of=20
ice and water.&nbsp; The slurry should be mostly ice. Avoid getting the =
ice=20
slurry in your solution.&nbsp; The crystals will be an emerald green=20
color.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Devise a procedure for determining the percent =

H<SUB>2</SUB>O while waiting.&nbsp; The final copy must be written in =
your lab=20
notebooks and must be verified by your TA with his or her signature. =
</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in"><B><I>Helpful=20
Hints:</I></B><I>&nbsp; The procedure to determine the percent of =
H<SUB>2</SUB>O=20
is very much like experiment 4, the hydrate experiment, in CHM =
151L.&nbsp; Some=20
things will need to be changed.</I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in"><B><I>1.<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></I></B><I>Notice that the procedure to determine percent =
H<SUB>2</SUB>O=20
is not part of the synthesis and purification of the iron salt crystals. =
It=20
determines one component (H<SUB>2</SUB>O) of the iron salt.&nbsp; =
So=85<U>Do not=20
combine the crystals dehydrated in the percent water procedure with the =
rest of=20
your crystals!</U></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><B>2.<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></B><I>In the formula=20
K<SUB>x</SUB>Fe(C<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>4</SUB>)<SUB>y</SUB></I><I><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol">=B7</SPAN>zH<SUB>2</SUB>O, the dot =
(</I><I><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Symbol">=B7</SPAN>) symbolizes that H<SUB>2</SUB>O =
is the=20
water of hydration.&nbsp; This means that the water is included in the =
lattice=20
structure of the iron salt. Hydrogen bonds and ion-dipole attractions =
hold it in=20
the crystal lattice. For these crystals, t<SPAN style=3D"COLOR: =
black">he water=20
can be removed from the crystal lattice of the iron salt by heating to=20
120</SPAN></I><I><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Symbol">=B0</SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: black">C to form the anhydrous iron salt.&nbsp; Heat the =
crystals=20
for about an hour.&nbsp;&nbsp; (WARNING: The crystals will start to =
decompose=20
after about two hours.) </SPAN></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in"><B><I>3.<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black">How much sample should =
you=20
use?&nbsp; (Definitely do not use all of the crystals, remember that you =
have 3=20
trials for this analysis.&nbsp; There are two more experiments where the =
iron=20
salt will be used.&nbsp; Together they use another 2 grams of iron =
salt.)=20
1.0-1.2g per trial is a good amount if you have enough sample. If the =
crystals=20
are large you may need to grind the up a bit to ensure complete =
dehydration.=20
<U>Remember to weigh the beaker before weighing your iron salt in=20
it.</U></SPAN></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in"><B><I>4.<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black">Spread the crystals out =
in the=20
bottom of a small beaker to ensure dehydration. Nest this inside a =
larger beaker=20
to prevent contamination (by falling over, spillage, etc.) of the sample =
while=20
in the oven.&nbsp; </SPAN></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in"><B><I>5.<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></I></B><B><I><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black">The larger or outer =
beakers must=20
be labeled with your name and section letter. Label the smaller beaker =
with a=20
pencil on the white part of the beaker.</SPAN></I></B></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in"><B><I>6.<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black">After heating, the =
dehydrated=20
samples should be cooled for 5 minutes and then placed in a desiccator =
for about=20
15 minutes (or until they get to room temperature).&nbsp; The crystals =
must be=20
cool to ensure that the balance reads the correct mass.&nbsp; =
</SPAN></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in"><I><SPAN =
style=3D"COLOR: black">A=20
<B>desiccator</B> is a seal-able container with a drying agent like=20
CaSO&shy;<SUB>4</SUB> or dierite in the bottom.&nbsp; The drying agent =
is an=20
anhydrous compound that absorbs water, keeping the desiccator=92s =
atmosphere=20
dry.</SPAN></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in"><B><I>7.<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black">Weigh the dehydrated =
crystals and=20
repeat steps 2 and 6 to ensure that all the water is removed from the =
sample=20
(Second heating should be for about 30 min.)</SPAN></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5in"><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black">Purification:&nbsp; =
</SPAN></B></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black">Decantation:</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black">&nbsp; After the crystals are =
formed,=20
remove the liquid or solvent by pouring it into another container. If =
you have a=20
good yield of crystals (at least 6 g or more) dispose of the filtrate by =
pouring=20
it down the sink.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent2 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
center"=20
align=3Dcenter><IMG height=3D92=20
src=3D"http://jan.ucc.nau.edu/~jkn/152A-SynthesisIronSalt_files/image002.=
jpg"=20
width=3D310></P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent2 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
center"=20
align=3Dcenter><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Figure A-2.&nbsp; =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Picture of the decanting process.</SPAN> </P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent2 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
center"=20
align=3Dcenter>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent2 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5in"><B><I>What is =

Decantation?</I></B><I>&nbsp; This is a process by which the solvent is =
poured=20
off of the crystals as shown in figure A-2. Removing the solvent at this =
point=20
removes excess reactants and unwanted side products (junk) found in the=20
solvent.</I></P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent2 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0in; TEXT-ALIGN: =
center"=20
align=3Dcenter>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black">Recrystallization:&nbsp; =
</SPAN></B></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black"></SPAN></B>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in"><B><I><SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: black">What is recrystallization?</SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN =

style=3D"COLOR: black">&nbsp; A process by which a minimum amount of hot =
pure=20
solvent used to dissolve the crystals and the solution is allowed to =
cool slowly=20
such that the crystals formed are much more pure. The solution is cooled =
slowly=20
to room temperature in the lockers to prevent impurities from being =
trapped in=20
the crystal structure.&nbsp; This process removes impurities and results =
in the=20
formation of larger crystals.</SPAN></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: 'Courier =
New'">o<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black">Add about 20 mL of RO water to =
the=20
crystals, break them up with a spatula, and gently heat and stir until =
they=20
dissolve.&nbsp; Be gentle with your spatula to avoid cracking the=20
beaker.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent3 style=3D"MARGIN-TOP: 6pt"><B><I><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 10pt">NOTE:</SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&nbsp; If a dark residue remains undissolved, =
allow it=20
to settle to the bottom, carefully decant the transparent green solution =
into=20
another beaker, and discard the residue. If decanting doesn=92t work try =
vacuum=20
filtration to remove the residue.</SPAN></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyTextIndent3=20
style=3D"MARGIN-BOTTOM: 6pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25in"><I><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&nbsp;If the crystals don=92t dissolve try =
adding water=20
(in 10 mL increments).&nbsp; Do not add more than an extra 30 mL.&nbsp; =
If this=20
doesn=92t work, see your TA</SPAN></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: 'Courier =
New'">o<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black">Cover the beaker with a watch =
glass or=20
parafilm and set in a bin until next lab.&nbsp; Each team member should =
record=20
the bin# the crystals are in.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: 'Courier New'">o<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =
</SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black">Each group should clean a small, =
amber=20
bottle, dry it, and store it in a group member's bin</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1in"><I><SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: black"></SPAN></I>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyText style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></SPAN><B>Before leaving, have TA sign and date notebook.</B></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal>&nbsp;</P>
<H3><B><U>Second Lab Period =96 Vacuum Filtration, Drying, and=20
Storage</U></B></H3>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN: 6pt =
0in"><I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp=
;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
<B>NOTE:</B>&nbsp; This will be done while doing Lab B =
(Calorimetry)&nbsp;=20
</I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-BOTTOM: 6pt"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
14pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
</SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Purification =
(cont.):</SPAN></B></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Vacuum Filtration.</SPAN></B></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: =
0.75in"><B><I>NOTE:</I></B><I>&nbsp;=20
Vacuum filtration is used to separate a solid from a liquid. In this =
case we=20
will separate the iron salt crystals from the aqueous solvent. Setup =
vacuum=20
filtration apparatus shown below in figure A-3 if not yet setup. The =
pressure=20
tubing is attached to the vacuum and filter paper placed in funnel. The =
vacuum=20
filtration apparatus should be cleaned and left on the lab bench after =
it is=20
used.&nbsp; </I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: center" align=3Dcenter><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Arial','sans-serif'"><IMG =
height=3D187=20
src=3D"http://jan.ucc.nau.edu/~jkn/152A-SynthesisIronSalt_files/image003.=
jpg"=20
width=3D185></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: center" =
align=3Dcenter><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Figure A-3.&nbsp; </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Vacuum Filtration Apparatus.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: center" align=3Dcenter><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Courier New'">o<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Cool a wash bottle of RO water in an ice=20
bath.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Courier New'">o<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Make sure the vacuum filtration apparatus, a =
glass=20
stirring rod, two 100 mL beakers, and one 250 mL beaker are =
clean.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Courier New'">o<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Put filter paper in the funnel, wet it with RO =
water (to=20
create a good seal), and turn the vacuum on.&nbsp; You should be able to =
see the=20
water being sucked out of the filter paper.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Courier New'">o<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Using the stirring rod or spatula, break up =
and pour the=20
crystals onto the filter paper in the funnel.</SPAN><B><I> </I></B></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Courier New'">o<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Rinse the beaker with about 25 mL of the cold =
water from=20
the wash bottle. Mix this around with the stir rod and quickly pour over =
the=20
crystals in the buchner filter funnel to rinse off impurities and =
transfer any=20
remaining crystals.&nbsp; Do this one to two more times. </SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Courier New'">o<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Leave the vacuum filter on for 2 to 3 minutes =
until=20
water is no longer dripping out of the funnel.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: 'Courier New'">o<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp;&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Turn off the vacuum and pour the solution =
(filtrate)=20
into a 250 mL beaker (do not mix this aqueous filtrate with acetone =
later).=20
</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in"><B></B>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.25in"><B><I>Helpful Hint=20
(2<SUP>nd</SUP> crop crystals):</I></B><I>&nbsp; The filtrate should be =
saved in=20
case you don=92t get at least 6 grams of crystals.&nbsp; See your TA =
about=20
this.</I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal>&nbsp;</P>
<P=20
class=3DMsoNormal>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&=
nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
<B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Drying Crystals:</SPAN></B></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN: 6pt 0in 0pt 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Take your buckner funnel with the crystals to =
the fume=20
hood and place it in the filter flask setup found there.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN: 6pt 0in 0pt 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Transfer about 15 mL of acetone into a 50mL =
beaker using=20
the pump dispenser in the fume hood. While the vacuum is on in the hood, =
wash=20
the crystals with about 15 mL of acetone.&nbsp; </SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN: 6pt 0in 0pt 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Rinse the crystals again with 15 mL of acetone =
and leave=20
for 1 to 2 minutes with the vacuum on to remove residual water and =
acetone from=20
the crystals.&nbsp; Dispose of the acetone solution in the filter flask =
by=20
placing it in the waste acetone bottle in the fume hood.&nbsp; (The =
acetone has=20
a low boiling point and therefore vaporizes more quickly than =
water.&nbsp; More=20
acetone than water on the crystals means the more quickly they will get=20
dry.)</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Take the buchner funnel with the crystals back =
to your=20
work bench and weigh the dry crystals in a 50 or 100 mL beaker.&nbsp; =
You should=20
have at least 6 grams. If not see your TA about </SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">a 2<SUP>nd</SUP> crop crystals mentioned=20
above.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Weigh the small amber bottle that was cleaned =
last=20
period and store the dried crystals in it with the lid off to the air to =
dry=20
them completely.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN: 6pt 0in 6pt 0.75in"><B><I>NOTE:</I></B><I>&nbsp; The =
crystals are=20
stored in an amber bottle because they decompose when exposed to light. =
</I></P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyText style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></SPAN><B>Before leaving, have TA sign and date notebook.</B></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in">&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><U><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Third Lab Period =
=96=20
Reweighing to get final mass of iron salt crystals </SPAN></U></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal=20
style=3D"MARGIN: 6pt 0in 0pt 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Reweigh the total amount of =
crystals</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New Roman'">&nbsp; </SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">During a later experiment, three or more =
simultaneous=20
trials will be done to determine the percent water in the iron salt =
crystals=20
your group made. You will use <U>your</U> percent water procedure to =
determine=20
the percent water in the iron salt during a later experiment.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyText style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></SPAN>Dispose of any filtrate solutions (except acetone) by =
washing them=20
down the drain. There is a waste bottle for acetone in the hood.<B> =
</B></P>
<P class=3DMsoBodyText style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.75in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Wingdings">n<SPAN style=3D"FONT: 7pt 'Times New =
Roman'">&nbsp;=20
</SPAN></SPAN><B>Before leaving have TA sign and date notebook.</B></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<H4><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">Post-Lab Error =
Analysis</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">:&nbsp; (This should be done when experiment A =
is=20
completed)&nbsp; </SPAN></H4>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
12pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =

After completing the last part of experiment A, comment on any problems =
with the=20
procedure and answer the following questions in your laboratory =
notebook. How=20
might the crystals be contaminated and what was done to prevent this? =
There are=20
no calculations, but the crystals will be analyzed in later experiments =
to=20
determine the percent by mass of the four components so that the =
empirical=20
formula can be determined. List the four components you will analyze for =
in the=20
iron salt, and do the following example empirical formula question in =
your lab=20
notebook:</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-TOP: 6pt"><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
12pt">What is=20
the empirical formula for a compound when a sample of it was found to =
contain=20
27.31% Ca, 48.06% Cl, and 25.43% H<SUB>2</SUB>O by mass? Is there a =
problem with=20
the data? (you will need to do a similar calculation after you finish =
experiment=20
F)&nbsp; <B>Show your work.</B></SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
12pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =

Each team member will <U>individually</U> do the calculations for a =
formal=20
scientific report (due later in the semester) on the synthesis and =
analysis of=20
the K<SUB>x</SUB>Fe(C<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>4</SUB>)<SUB>y</SUB></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; FONT-FAMILY: Symbol">=B7</SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">zH<SUB>2</SUB>O crystals.&nbsp; For the =
report, <U>only=20
the data</U> can be collected as a group.&nbsp; More information on the =
report=20
will be provided at the end of experiment F.</SPAN></P>
